y, demands for political representation, and perceived threats to the patriarchal order during the war years sustained one arena of cultural debate. New modes of popular entertainment, including cinema, cabaret, and variety shows, created another, particularly as they challenged elite notions of propriety. Blobaum presents these themes in comparative context, not only with other major European cities during the Great War but also with Warsaw under Nazi German occupation a generation later.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspectszPolandzWarsaw. 4aMilitary History. 4aWorld War I. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package 2017z978311062534908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311066587108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016-2017z978311060673740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501707889423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501707889.jpg  a978-3-11-060673-7  Cornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016-2017c2016d2017  a978-3-11-062534-9  COR eBook Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-066587-1  COR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG